<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd">
<en-note><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">FAQ</span></div><div><span style="font-style: italic; text-decoration: underline;">Where all default </span><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; text-decoration: underline;">ENVIRONMENT VARs </span><span style="font-style: italic; text-decoration: underline;">settings are?</span></div><div>=&gt; sudo <span style="font-weight: bold;">vim</span><span style="font-style: italic;"> /etc/login.conf     </span>( please the file if you wanna modify some VARs )</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">How do I read the running Kernel Options?</span></div><div>Method 1 =&gt;<span style="font-weight: bold;"> strings</span> /boot/kernel/kernel</div><div>Method 2 =&gt; <span style="font-weight: bold;">dmesg -a</span></div><div># =&gt; strings /boot/kernel/kernel | grep -i xenhvm</div><div># =&gt; dmesg -a | grep -i xen</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">How do I remove the config options after installing a port?</span></div><div><span># Go to a port which you want to remove already set config</span></div><div><br/></div><div>[/usr/ports/.../app] =&gt; <span style="font-weight: bold;">make rmconfig</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">How do I know with what options was  a port built?</span></div><div> [/usr/ports/.../app] =&gt;<span style="font-weight: bold;"> make showconfig </span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">How do I know if the process is a zombie?</span></div><div>=&gt; ps aux | awk '$8==&quot;Z&quot; {print $2}'</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; text-decoration: underline;">How do I create a man page file?</span></div><div>=&gt; <span style="font-weight: bold;">man </span>fstab | <span style="font-weight: bold;">col</span> <span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">-b</span> &gt; fstab<span style="font-style: italic;">.txt   </span># This will create the &quot;fstab&quot; man page as the text file &quot;fstab.txt&quot;</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; text-decoration: underline;">Is there way to say auto &quot;yes&quot; to all question?</span></div><div>(Make Install say &quot;Yes&quot; to all:)</div><div>Method 1:  <span style="font-weight: bold;">export </span><span style="font-style: italic;">BATCH</span>=&quot;yes&quot;  and pass option &quot;<span style="font-style: italic;">-DBATCH</span>&quot;  just before the work <span style="font-style: italic;">install</span></div><div>Method 2: =&gt; <span style="font-weight: bold;">env</span> <span style="font-style: italic;">BATCH</span>=yes <span style="font-weight: bold;">make</span> <span style="font-style: italic;">-DBATCH</span> <span style="font-weight: bold;">install</span> </div><div> </div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; text-decoration: underline;">How do I know how much &quot;free&quot; memory available?</span></div><div>=&gt; <span style="font-weight: bold;">top</span><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;"> </span><span style="font-style: italic;">-d 1 </span>| <span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">grep</span><span style="font-style: italic;"> '^Mem:'  </span>| <span style="font-style: italic;"> </span><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">cut </span><span style="font-style: italic;">-d ',' -f 6</span></div><div><br/><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; text-decoration: underline;">Mounting an ISO Image:</span></div><div>=&gt; mdconfig -a -t vnode -f /path/to/iso_image.iso -u 1</div><div>=&gt; mount -t cd9660  /dev/md1 /mnt/cdrom</div><div><br/></div><div>To reverse the process:</div><div>=&gt; mount -u /mnt/cdrom</div><div>=&gt; mdconfig -d -u 1</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; text-decoration: underline;">How To make a colour terminal out put?</span></div><div>=&gt; cd /usr/ports/misc/gnuls  </div><div>=&gt; make install clean</div><div><br/></div><div>alias ls=&quot;gnuls --color=auto  --show-control-chars&quot;</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;">How to setup up SSH auto-login:</span></div><div>Our client is the CentOS machine</div><div>Our Server is the FreeBSD Datacenter</div><div><br/></div><div>(i) On the Client side :</div><div>    =&gt; ssh-keygen -t rsa -d 1024  # 2048, 4096 </div><div><br/></div><div>(ii) FreeBSD Server:</div><div>     =&gt; mkdir .ssh &amp;&amp; chmod 0700 .ssh</div><div><br/></div><div>(iii) On the Client side:</div><div>     =&gt; cd ~/.ssh</div><div>     =&gt; scp id_rsa.pub khasanov@10.10.10.100:/home/khasanov/.ssh/authorized_keys</div><div><span> Note: </span>You might also need to change  =&gt; <span style="font-weight: bold;">chmod </span><span>640</span></div><div> <span style="font-style: italic;">authorized_keys</span></div><div>           and make sure that you have  <span style="font-weight: bold;">PubkeyAuthentication</span> </div><div><span style="font-style: italic;">yes</span><span> </span></div><div>in the &quot;sshd_config&quot; file</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;">Why SSH takes too long to ask for password?</span></div><div>It is the DNS reverse IP address problem: Edit the &quot;/etc/ssh/sshd_config&quot;</div><div>and set <span style="font-weight: bold;">UseDNS </span><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">no</span></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>The portaudit tool is now obsolete, please remove portaudit and use the</div><div>command 'pkg audit' instead.  See man pkg-audit(8) for more information.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;">How do change the Hostname without rebooting?</span></div><div><br/></div><div>=&gt; hostname &lt;newname&gt;</div><div>Edit the &quot;/etc/rc.conf&quot; and change the name to make permanent.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>
